ks]] Head Coach, and former WKU Head Coach from 2010 to 2012, and played QB from 1995 to 1998\n*[[Eagle Keys|Eagle \"Buddy\" Keys]] \u2013 Former Head Coach in the [[Canadian Football League|CFL]], [[Grey Cup]] Champion, member of the [[Canadian Football Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Rod Smart]] \u2013 former running back for the [[Carolina Panthers]] and [[Las Vegas Outlaws (XFL)]]. More famously known by the nickname \"He Hate Me\".\n*[[Jason Michael]] \u2013 QB of 2002 National Championship team, Current Offensive Coordinator for [[Tennessee Titans]]\n*[[Brandon Doughty]]  \u2013 2014 Sammy Baugh Award Winner and all-time passing leader at WKU\n*[[George Fant]] \u2013 Former [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers basketball]] star and current offensive tackle for the [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n\n== Notable Hilltopper coaches ==\n\n=== Head coaches ===\n\n* L.T. Smith (1920\u20131921, Head Coach) \u2013 Namesake of [[L.T. Smith Stadium]]\n* [[Edgar Diddle|E.A. Diddle]] (1922\u20131928, Head Coach) \u2013 Legendary [[WKU Hilltoppers basketball]] Head Coach, symbol behind for WKU's red towel logo, and namesake of [[E. A. Diddle Arena]]\n* Nick Denes (1957\u20131967, Head Coach) \u2013 Namesake of [[Nick Denes Field]]\n* [[Jimmy Feix]] (1968\u20131983, Head Coach; 1957\u20131967, Assistant Coach; 1986\u20131991, Athletic Director) \u2013 Winningest coach in WKU history; 1973, 1978, and 1980 Ohio Valley Conference Coach of the Year; 1973 and 1975 NCAA Division II National Runners-up, and namesake of Feix Field in L.T. Smith Stadium.\n* [[Jack Harbaugh]] (1989\u20132002, Head Coach) \u2013 2000 Ohio Valley Conference Coach of the Year, 2002 [[AFCA Coach of the Year]] (FCS), 2002 FCS National Champion\n* [[Bobby Petrino]] (2013) \u2013 Former coach at University of Louisville, University of Arkansas, and the NFL's Atlanta Falcons spent 13 months as head coach at WKU before returning to Louisville in January 2014\n\n=== Assistants ===\n\n* [[Tommy Prothro]] (1942, Assistant Coach) \u2013 Former Head Coach \u2013 [[Oregon State]] and [[UCLA]], Former Head Coach \u2013 [[Los Angeles Rams]] and [[San Diego Chargers]], member of the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Jerry Glanville]] (1967, Defensive Coordinator) \u2013 Former Head Coach of the Houston Oilers and the [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n* [[Jim Harbaugh]] (1994\u20132001, Assistant Coach) \u2013 Former [[National Football League|NFL]] Head Coach for the [[San Francisco 49ers]] and current Head Coach at the [[University of Michigan]], was a certified, unpaid assistant under his father while playing in the NFL\n* [[Don Martindale]] \u2013 (2001\u201303, LB Coach, Defensive Coordinator) Current Linebackers coach for the [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n\n==Retired jerseys==\nWestern Kentucky has retired four jersey numbers.<ref name=\"2017MG\" />{{RP|143}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|No.|Name|Years|Retired}}\n|-\n| '''1''' || [[Willie Taggart]] || 1995\u20131998 || 1999\n|-\n| '''24''' || [[Virgil Livers]] || 1971\u20131974 || 2001\n|-\n| '''44''' || [[Dale Lindsey]] || 1963\u20131964 || 2007\n|-\n| '''66''' || [[Jimmy Feix]] || 1949\u20131952 || 1999\n|}\n\n==Individual award winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Award<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Name\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Year(s)\n|-\n|[[Ohio Valley Conference]] Coach of the Year\n|Nick Denes\n[[Jimmy Feix]]\n\n[[Jack Harbaugh]]\n|1963\n1973, 1978, 1980\n\n2000\n|-\n|Division I-AA [[AFCA Coach of the Year]]\n|[[Jack Harbaugh]]\n|2002\n|-\n|[[Gateway Football Conference]] Freshman of the Year\n|Justin Haddix\n|2003\n|-\n|[[Sun Belt Conference]] Player of the Year\n|[[Antonio Andrews]]\n|2013\n|-\n|[[Sun Belt Conference]] Offensive Player of the Year\n|[[Bobby Rainey]]\n[[Antonio Andrews]]\n|2010, 2011\n2013\n|-\n|[[Sun Belt Conference]] Defensive Player of the Year\n|[[Quanterus Smith]]\nXavius Boyd\n|2012\n2013\n|-\n|[[Sammy Baugh Trophy]] Award Winner\n|[[Brandon Doughty]]\n|2014\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Most Valuable Player\n|[[Brandon Doughty]]\n|2014, 2015\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Defensive Player of the Year\n|DeAngelo Malone\n|2019\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Newcomer of the Year\n|Ty Storey\n|2019\n|-\n|[[Conference USA]] Coach of the Year\n|[[Tyson Helton]]\n|2019\n|}\n\n==All-Americans==\nFive players have been designated by the NCAA as \"Consensus All-Americans\" as of 2017.<ref name=\"2017MG\" />{{RP|137}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|Player|Position|Year}}\n|-\n| James Edwards || [[Free safety|FS]] || 1987\n|-\n| [[Bobby Sippio]] || [[Cornerback|CB]] || 2000\n|-\n| [[Mel Mitchell]] || [[Safety (gridiron football position)|S]] || 2001\n|-\n| Chris Price || [[Guard (American football)|G]] || 2002\n|-\n| Buster Ashley || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] || 2004\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\nWKU has several historic rivalries that stem from its time in the [[Ohio Valley Conference]]. Since WKU's transition to the [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] in 2007, two of these rivalry games are no longer played on an annual basis.\n\n===Middle Tennessee State===\n{{Main|100 Miles of Hate}}\n[[Middle Tennessee\u2013Western Kentucky football rivalry|100 Miles of Hate]] is the name of the long-standing rivalry with [[Middle Tennessee State Blue Raiders football|Middle Tennessee]]. As WKU's oldest rivalry the two programs played together for several decades in the [[Ohio Valley Conference]] before both became members of the [[Sun Belt Conference]] and then transitioned to [[Conference USA]] about the same time. The name comes from the fact that the two universities are separated by about 100 miles.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Games played\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |First meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Last meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win streak\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Wins\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Losses\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Ties\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win %\n|-\n|67\n|1914, MTSU 47\u20130\n|2018, MTSU 29\u201310\n|3, WKU (2015\u20132017)\n|32\n|34\n|1\n|.492\n|}\n\n===Eastern Kentucky===\n{{Main|Battle of the Bluegrass}}\nWKY's has an inactive rivalry with [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]. The two programs have met 84 times in football since 1914. The rivalry has taken a hiatus since leaving EKU behind as WKU transitioned to FBS in 2009. The programs scheduled a one-game match-up in 2017 in which WKU won 31\u201317 in Bowling Green, KY.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Games played\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |First meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Last meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win streak\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Wins\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Losses\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Ties\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win %\n|-\n|85\n|1914, EKU 34\u20136\n|2017, WKU 37\u201313\n|3, WKU (2007\u20132017)\n|47\n|35\n|3\n|.571\n|}\n\n===Murray State===\n{{Main|Battle for the Red Belt}}\nWKU has an inactive rivalry with nearby [[Murray State Racers football|Murray State]]. The two programs have met 67 times since the rivalry began in 1931. The Red Belt trophy was introduced to the rivalry series in 1978 when Murray's athletic trainer failed to pack a belt for the Racers' road trip and was loaned one by legendary WKU athletic trainer Bill \"Doc E\" Edwards.<ref>[http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400&ATCLID=1584257] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302221804/http://www.wkusports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=5400&ATCLID=1584257|date=March 2, 2012}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Games played\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |First meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Last meeting\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win streak\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Wins\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Losses\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Ties\n!style=\"background:#B01E24; color:white;\" |Win %\n|-\n|67\n|1931, WKU 7\u20130\n|2008, WKU 50\u20139\n|4, WKU (1999\u20132008)\n|36\n|24\n|7\n|.589\n|}\n\n==Future non-conference opponents==\nAnnounced schedules as of January 27, 2020.<ref name=\"nonconfopp\">{{cite web|title=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers Football Future Schedules|publisher=FBSchedules.com|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/wku/|accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Western Kentucky Hilltoppers|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027|2028}}\n|-\n| [[Chattanooga Mocs football|Chattanooga]]\n| [[UT Martin Skyhawks football|UT Martin]]\n| [[Austin Peay Governors football|Austin Peay]]\n| [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]] \n| at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| at [[Liberty Flames football|Liberty]]\n| at [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n| at [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| at [[Miami Redhawks football|Miami (OH)]]\n|- \n| at [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]\n| at [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n| at [[Hawaii Warriors football|Hawaii]]\n| [[Houston Baptist Huskies football|Houston Baptist]]\n| [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]]\n| at [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]]\n| [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| [[Miami Redhawks football|Miami (OH)]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Liberty Flames football|Liberty]]\n| [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]\n| at [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]]\n| at [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]\n| [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]]\n| [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| at [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| at [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]]\n| [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]]\n| at [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]]\n| at [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| \n| \n| at [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{WKU Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{Western Kentucky University}}\n{{Conference USA football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|*]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1908]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in Kentucky]]\n", "name_user": "MHS1976", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWillie Taggart (2010\u20132012):Added links to team pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Kentucky_Hilltoppers_football"}
{"title_page": "Moorside High School, Swinton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name          = Moorside High School\n|image         =https://ibb.co/7rPZQzV \n|image_size          =1000x1000 \n|caption       =Moorside High School Logo \n|coordinates   = {{coord|53.508|-2.347|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|motto         = Together We Believe, Achieve, Succeed.\t\t\t\n|established   = 1934\t\t\n|closed        = \n|type          = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n|head_label    = Headteacher\t\n|head          = Mr K. Bardsley\n|chair_label   = Chair of Governors\n|chair         = Mr C Read\n|city          = [[Swinton, Greater Manchester|Swinton]], [[City of Salford|Salford]]\n|country       = [[England]]\n|local_authority = [[Salford City Council|Salford]]\n|urn           = 105977\n|ofsted        = yes\n|enrolment    = 1050pupils<ref name=\"ofsted\">[http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/105977 Moorside High School] Retrieved 1 February 2019.</ref>\n|gender        = [[Coeducational|Mixed]]\n|lower_age     = 11\n|upper_age     = 16 \n|website       = http://www.moorsidehigh.co.uk\n}}\n\n'''Moorside High School,''' established in 1934, is a [[secondary school]] located in [[Swinton, Greater Manchester|Swinton]], [[City of Salford|Salford]], near [[Manchester]], [[England]]. The school was located on the south side of the [[A580 road|East Lancashire Road]], to the south of Swinton town centre within the Salford Local Authority before being completely rebuilt in recent years.\n\n==Admissions==\nLike all schools in Salford [[Local Education Authority|LEA]], it is for ages 11\u201316 with no [[sixth form]], because it is Local Authority run there is no exam to pass to gain entry into the school, local pupils are automatically placed into the nearest high school. However, if they wish to attend a certain high school they must complete the relevant forms and send them to Salford City Council as early as they can before the following academic year as places at the school are limited to 1,050. As of 2017 the school has 1,051 pupils attending. Moorside Primary School is the main feeder school locally with St Peter's CE Primary School in [[Swinton, Greater Manchester|Swinton]] also being a feeder school in the area.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==History==\nThe school was originally located between the [[A580 road|East Lancashire Road]] and Wentworth Road in Swinton.\n\n===Phil Neville's flying visit to pupils===\nIn November 2007, England footballer [[Phil Neville]] visited the school by helicopter to thank pupils for supporting the New Children's Hospital Appeal. The school held a 20-minute question and answer session with Neville before being given a brief presentation about the New Children's Hospital Appeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/phils-flying-visit-to-pupils-1010675|title=Phil's flying visit to pupils|work=Manchester Evening News|date=13 November 2007|author=Rooth, Ben|publisher=M.E.N. Media|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Specialist College Status===\nIn 2008 the school was granted special status in Mathematics and Computing.<ref name=\"ofsted\"/> The school continues to improve in all aspects of the curriculum.\n\n===Death of former Deputy Headteacher===\nIn 2008, a former deputy headteacher, Paul Simpson, 53, suffered a heart attack as he took part in a five-a-side game at [[Falinge Park High School]], in [[Rochdale]]. He was rushed to [[Rochdale Infirmary]], where he died.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/teacher-died-playing-game-he-loved-939844|title=Teacher died playing game he loved|work=Manchester Evening News|date=16 January 2008|author=Keegan, Mike|publisher=M.E.N. Media|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Strike ===\nIn 2018, teachers at the school who were members of the [[NASUWT]] union, took part in five days of industrial action in protest at \"adverse management culture\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/teachers-strike-salford-high-school-15350385|title=Teachers to strike at Salford school in row over 'adverse management culture'|last=Dobson|first=Charlotte|date=2018-10-31|website=men|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.union-news.co.uk/teachers-on-strike-in-salford/|title=Teachers on strike in Salford|date=2018-10-31|website=Union News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Site==\nThe school was rebuilt between 2011 and 2013 with trees being removed from the Deans playing field and a new entrance from the [[A580 road|East Lancashire Road]]. The new buildings opened in September 2013.\n\nMoorside Primary School is located on the same site in a purpose built part of the main building.\n\n==Academic performance==\nIt gets average [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] results and above average for Salford. The 2010 year group achieved 67% A*-Cs in all subjects with the Avg GCSE Points being 418.6.<ref name=\"GCSE league tables: North West\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/leaguetables/6980178/GCSE-league-tables-North-West.html|title=GCSE league tables: North West|work=The Telegraph|location=London|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref><br>\n'''Moorside High School''' has been improving its GCSE results for the past five years:\n*2006 with 10% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2007 with 20% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2008 with 13% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2009 with 15% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2010 with 7% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C.<ref name=\"GCSE league tables: North West\"/>\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at Moorside High School}}\nNotable past pupils include:\n*British actress [[Raffey Cassidy]] attended the school between 2013 and 2016, where she then moved to another school in the area. \n*English composer [[Peter Maxwell Davies]] who attended between 1939 and 1944.\n*Former [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] footballer [[Ryan Giggs]] who attended between 1985 and 1990\n*Former [[CITV]] presenter [[Danielle Nicholls]], who attended between 1989 and 1994\n*Former [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]] RL player [[Harrison Hansen]] who attended between 1997 and 2002\n*[[Hollyoaks]] actress [[Jorgie Porter]] who attended between 1999 and 2004\n*Actor & former [[CBBC]] Presenter [[Chris Johnson (presenter)|Chris Johnson]] who attended between 2002 and 2007\n*[[David Robinson (rugby league)|Dave Robinson]] 1960s/1970s RL forward with [[Swinton Lions|Swinton]], [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], [[Lancashire rugby league team|Lancashire]] and [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]], born 1 August 1944\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n*[http://www.moorsidehigh.co.uk Official Website]\n \t\n{{Schools in Salford}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Salford]]\n[[Category:Community schools in Salford]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Swinton, Greater Manchester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name          = Moorside High School\n|image         =https://ibb.co/7rPZQzV \n|image_size          =1000x1000 \n|caption       =Moorside High School Logo \n|coordinates   = {{coord|53.508|-2.347|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|motto         = Together We Believe, Achieve, Succeed.\t\t\t\n|established   = 1934\t\t\n|closed        = \n|type          = [[Community school (England and Wales)|Community school]]\n|head_label    = Headteacher\t\n|head          = Mr K. Bardsley\n|chair_label   = Chair of Governors\n|chair         = Mr C Read\n|city          = [[Swinton, Greater Manchester|Swinton]], [[City of Salford|Salford]]\n|country       = [[England]]\n|local_authority = [[Salford City Council|Salford]]\n|urn           = 105977\n|ofsted        = yes\n|enrolment    = 1050pupils<ref name=\"ofsted\">[http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/105977 Moorside High School] Retrieved 1 February 2019.</ref>\n|gender        = [[Coeducational|Mixed]]\n|lower_age     = 11\n|upper_age     = 16 \n|website       = http://www.moorsidehigh.co.uk\n}}\n\n'''Moorside High School,''' established in 1934, is a [[secondary school]] located in [[Swinton, Greater Manchester|Swinton]], [[City of Salford|Salford]], near [[Manchester]], [[England]]. The school was located on the south side of the [[A580 road|East Lancashire Road]], to the south of Swinton town centre within the Salford Local Authority before being completely rebuilt in recent years.\n\n==Admissions==\nLike all schools in Salford [[Local Education Authority|LEA]], it is for ages 11\u201316 with no [[sixth form]], because it is Local Authority run there is no exam to pass to gain entry into the school, local pupils are automatically placed into the nearest high school. However, if they wish to attend a certain high school they must complete the relevant forms and send them to Salford City Council as early as they can before the following academic year as places at the school are limited to 1,050. As of 2017 the school has 1,051 pupils attending. Moorside Primary School is the main feeder school locally with St Peter's CE Primary School in [[Swinton, Greater Manchester|Swinton]] also being a feeder school in the area.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==History==\nThe school was originally located between the [[A580 road|East Lancashire Road]] and Wentworth Road in Swinton.\n\n===Phil Neville's flying visit to pupils===\nIn November 2007, England footballer [[Phil Neville]] visited the school by helicopter to thank pupils for supporting the New Children's Hospital Appeal. The school held a 20-minute question and answer session with Neville before being given a brief presentation about the New Children's Hospital Appeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/phils-flying-visit-to-pupils-1010675|title=Phil's flying visit to pupils|work=Manchester Evening News|date=13 November 2007|author=Rooth, Ben|publisher=M.E.N. Media|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Specialist College Status===\nIn 2008 the school was granted special status in Mathematics and Computing.<ref name=\"ofsted\"/> The school continues to improve in all aspects of the curriculum.\n\n===Death of former Deputy Headteacher===\nIn 2008, a former deputy headteacher, Paul Simpson, 53, suffered a heart attack as he took part in a five-a-side game at [[Falinge Park High School]], in [[Rochdale]]. He was rushed to [[Rochdale Infirmary]], where he died.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/teacher-died-playing-game-he-loved-939844|title=Teacher died playing game he loved|work=Manchester Evening News|date=16 January 2008|author=Keegan, Mike|publisher=M.E.N. Media|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== '''Strike''' ===\nIn 2018, teachers at the school who were members of the [[NASUWT]] union, took part in five days of industrial action in protest at \"adverse management culture\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/teachers-strike-salford-high-school-15350385|title=Teachers to strike at Salford school in row over 'adverse management culture'|last=Dobson|first=Charlotte|date=2018-10-31|website=men|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.union-news.co.uk/teachers-on-strike-in-salford/|title=Teachers on strike in Salford|date=2018-10-31|website=Union News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Site==\nThe school was rebuilt between 2011 and 2013 with trees being removed from the Deans playing field and a new entrance from the [[A580 road|East Lancashire Road]]. The new buildings opened in September 2013.\n\nMoorside Primary School is located on the same site in a purpose built part of the main building.\n\n==Academic performance==\nIt gets average [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] results and above average for Salford. The 2010 year group achieved 67% A*-Cs in all subjects with the Avg GCSE Points being 418.6.<ref name=\"GCSE league tables: North West\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/leaguetables/6980178/GCSE-league-tables-North-West.html|title=GCSE league tables: North West|work=The Telegraph|location=London|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref><br>\n'''Moorside High School''' has been improving its GCSE results for the past five years:\n*2006 with 10% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2007 with 20% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2008 with 13% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2009 with 15% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C\n*2010 with 7% of pupils achieving 5 A*-C.<ref name=\"GCSE league tables: North West\"/>\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at Moorside High School}}\nNotable past pupils include:\n*British actress [[Raffey Cassidy]] attended the school between 2013 and 2016, where she then moved to another school in the area. \n*English composer [[Peter Maxwell Davies]] who attended between 1939 and 1944.\n*Former [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] footballer [[Ryan Giggs]] who attended between 1985 and 1990\n*Former [[CITV]] presenter [[Danielle Nicholls]], who attended between 1989 and 1994\n*Former [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]] RL player [[Harrison Hansen]] who attended between 1997 and 2002\n*[[Hollyoaks]] actress [[Jorgie Porter]] who attended between 1999 and 2004\n*Actor & former [[CBBC]] Presenter [[Chris Johnson (presenter)|Chris Johnson]] who attended between 2002 and 2007\n*[[David Robinson (rugby league)|Dave Robinson]] 1960s/1970s RL forward with [[Swinton Lions|Swinton]], [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], [[Lancashire rugby league team|Lancashire]] and [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]], born 1 August 1944\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n*[http://www.moorsidehigh.co.uk Official Website]\n \t\n{{Schools in Salford}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Salford]]\n[[Category:Community schools in Salford]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Swinton, Greater Manchester]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Heading with bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moorside_High_School,_Swinton"}
{"title_page": "Say Nothing (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->\n| name       = Say Nothing\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Theory of a Deadman]]\n| cover      = TOAD_Say_Nothing_album_cover.jpg\n| alt        = An image of palm trees seen on a blue background as if being seen as a reflection on a body of water. The entire image is surrounded by a thick black border. The word \"Theory\" is seen in the middle while the phrase \"Say Nothing\" is displayed in the bottom right corner.\n| border     = yes\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|01|31|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = April\u2013May 2019<ref name=\"Recording Record Seven\">Recording dates for ''Say Nothing'':\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BvIQv4AHoMD/|title=Record 7 is upon us!! We start recording in april in jolly ole England with #martinterefe so stay tuned!! #theory #record7|date=March 17, 2019|publisher=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByIG9JZFMgi/|title=@theory_dean slappin da bass. Today is officially our last day here before we fly home and get ready for summer touring!! #theory7 #london|date=May 31, 2019|publisher=Instagram|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n| studio     = Kensaltown, The Panic Room, Eastcote Studio 4\n| genre      =\n| length     = 35:01\n| label      =\n* [[604 Records|604]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n| producer   = [[Martin Terefe]]\n| prev_title = [[Wake Up Call (Theory of a Deadman album)|Wake Up Call]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Say Nothing\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\n | single1date = September 25, 2019\n | single2     = World Keeps Spinning\n | single2date = January 24, 2020\n }}\n}}\n\n'''''Say Nothing''''' is the seventh studio album by Canadian rock band [[Theory of a Deadman]], released on January 31, 2020, through [[604 Records]] in Canada and [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] and [[Roadrunner Records]] in the United States. The record contains lyrics about such issues as domestic violence and racism. The band opted to continue their collaboration with Swedish music producer [[Martin Terefe]]\u2014who worked with them on their previous album ''[[Wake Up Call (Theory of a Deadman album)|Wake Up Call]]''\u2014returning to [[London]] in April 2019. Their prior album marked the group's departure from their usual hard rock sound to a more pop- and pop rock-infused style and was met with mixed reviews from critics.\n\n==Background and development==\n[[Theory of a Deadman]]'s sound had been firmly rooted in the [[Alternative rock|alternative]] and [[hard rock]] genres since the band signed a record deal with [[Chad Kroeger]]'s [[604 Records]] in 2001. Lead singer Tyler Connolly stated that after the release of their fourth studio album, ''[[The Truth Is... (Theory of a Deadman album)|The Truth Is...]]'', in 2011, the band was receiving pressure from their record label to create an album that was \"more poppy\". He believed the label was \"getting tired of [their] fun rock stuff\" and \"wanted to hear something different\". The band responded to this pressure with the release of their fifth studio album, ''[[Savages (Theory of a Deadman album)|Savages]]'', in 2014, which Connolly described as the \"opposite\" of their record label's wishes.<ref name=\"NRR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalrockreview.com/interviews/tyler-connolly-of-theory-of-a-deadman|title=Tyler Connolly of Theory of a Deadman|last=Kennedy|first=Adam|date=March 6, 2016|publisher=[[National Rock Review]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914033121/http://www.nationalrockreview.com/interviews/tyler-connolly-of-theory-of-a-deadman|archive-date=September 14, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Los Angeles-based music producer [[Howard Benson]] worked with the band on ''Savages'' as well as three of their previous albums,<ref name=\"SurreyNow-Leader\">{{cite web|url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/entertainment/rx-medicate-the-biggest-song-of-theory-of-a-deadmans-16-year-career-north-delta-bassist-raves/|title='Rx (Medicate)' the Biggest Song of Theory of a Deadman's 16-year Career, North Delta Bassist Raves|last=Zillich|first=Tom|website=[[The Now (newspaper)|Surrey Now-Leader]]|date=December 15, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518173856/https://www.surreynowleader.com/entertainment/rx-medicate-the-biggest-song-of-theory-of-a-deadmans-16-year-career-north-delta-bassist-raves/|archive-date=May 18, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but the group felt they wanted something different for their future records. Connolly stated that their [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] team mentioned Swedish music producer, [[Martin Terefe]], who was known for working with pop rock music artists such as [[Jason Mraz]], [[James Blunt]], and [[Train (band)|Train]], and was interested in collaborating with the group. Theory of a Deadman spent seven weeks in London in 2016, recording at Terefe's Kensaltown Studios.<ref name=\"SurreyNow-Leader\" /><ref name=\"Two Doods Reviews 1\">{{cite AV media|title=10 Questions with Tyler Connolly from Theory of a Deadman|url=https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|time=2:14|publisher=Two Doods Reviews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611080003/https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe band's sixth studio album ''[[Wake Up Call (Theory of a Deadman album)|Wake Up Call]]'', released in October 2017, has been described by critics as a departure from Theory of a Deadman's usual hard rock foundation, moving into [[Pop music|pop]] and [[pop rock]] territory.<ref name=\"Alternative Addiction\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/Review/1661|title=Album Review of Wake Up Call by Theory of a Deadman|website=[[Alternative Addiction]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308100837/http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/Review/1661|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Spokesman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/nov/09/theory-of-a-deadman-trade-hard-rock-for-pop-rock-o/#/0|title=Theory of a Deadman Trade Hard Rock for Pop-rock on 'Wake Up Call'|last=Podplesky|first=Azaria|website=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231211932/http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/nov/09/theory-of-a-deadman-trade-hard-rock-for-pop-rock-o/#/0|archive-date=December 31, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The band credited this shift to Connolly, the group's primary songwriter, acquiring and learning how to play the [[piano]] prior to the album's recording. Connolly expressed feeling creatively exhausted, stating, \"For some reason, [on] this album, I felt tapped on the guitar side. I felt like every riff was written.\"<ref name=\"Two Doods Reviews 2\">{{cite AV media|title=10 Questions with Tyler Connolly from Theory of a Deadman|url=https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|time=1:45|publisher=Two Doods Reviews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611080003/https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bassist Dean Back agreed, saying, \"During the writing process, Tyler\u2019s go-to was to always pick up a guitar and write with that. He pushed himself through and instead of writing with the guitar he used a piano he has in his house. ... I think writing on the piano opened up another creative realm in him.\"<ref name=\"AXS1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-theory-of-a-deadman-s-dean-back-on-their-new-sound-for-wake--124476|title=Interview: Theory of a Deadman\u2019s Dean Back on Their New Sound for 'Wake Up Call'|last=Allegrezza|first=Kim|publisher=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|date=October 22, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141119/https://www.axs.com/interview-theory-of-a-deadman-s-dean-back-on-their-new-sound-for-wake--124476|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The album was met with mixed reviews from critics with some praising the lyrical maturity that was lacking in previous albums, and others criticizing it for the sudden change in genre.<ref name=\"Wake Up Call Review 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/wake-up-call-mw0003090487|title=Wake Up Call \u2013 Theory of a Deadman|last=Monter|first=James Christopher|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613020229/https://www.allmusic.com/album/wake-up-call-mw0003090487|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Wake Up Call Review 2\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.uberrock.co.uk/cd-reviews/31-november-cd/19761-theory-of-a-deadman-wake-up-call-roadrunner-records604-records.html|title=Theory of a Deadman \u2013 'Wake Up Call'|last=D|first=Jonni|work=\u00dcber Rock|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116140441/http://www.uberrock.co.uk/cd-reviews/31-november-cd/19761-theory-of-a-deadman-wake-up-call-roadrunner-records604-records.html|archive-date=January 16, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}\n</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n''Say Nothing'' has been described by the band as a \"continuation of the last record\",<ref name=\"Substream Interview\">{{cite web|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2020/01/interview-theory-connolly-world-spinning/|title=Exclusive: Theory Drop Video for \"World Keeps Spinning\" + Interview w/ Tyler Connolly|last=White|first=Logan|date=January 31, 2020|website=[[Substream Magazine]]|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and Connolly acknowledged a sense of anxiety while recording the album due to the pressure created by the success of ''Wake Up Call'''s [[lead single]], \"[[Rx (Medicate)]]\" (a song that addresses [[Substance abuse|prescription drug abuse]]).<ref name=\"Billboard Say Nothing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8546128/theory-of-a-deadman-say-nothing|title=Theory of a Deadman's 'Say Nothing': Premiere|last=Graff|first=Gary|authorlink=Gary Graff|date=December 13, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Although Theory of a Deadman have avoided having their lyrics surround social and political issues, the positive feedback they received for \"Rx (Medicate)\" influenced their decision to speak about important topics related to [[domestic violence]], [[racism]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and [[anxiety]], and politics.<ref name=\"Artist Waves\">{{cite web|url=https://artistwaves.com/speaking-up-with-say-nothing-by-tyler-connolly-theory-of-a-deadman/|title=Speaking Up with \"Say Nothing\" by: Tyler Connolly / Theory of a Deadman|last=Connolly|first=Tyler|date=November 5, 2019|publisher=Artist Waves|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Connolly said, \"This album allowed me to say all of the things that were on my mind earlier, but I was too afraid to say. Our previous material was pretty much all relationship-driven. Everything was about me being unhappy. This one was about what's going on in the world, the state of American politics, and everything else. It was a completely different way of writing for us.\"<ref name=\"Commodore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.commodoreballroom.com/view-all/2020/1/31/theory|title=Say Nothing World Tour 2020|publisher=[[Commodore Ballroom]]|accessdate=September 26, 2019}}</ref> Guitarist Dave Brenner added, \"I look at the record as a microcosm of our current era. It's a reminder to look inward at what's happening and what we're becoming. ... Maybe we can give the world a little solace and encourage everyone to treat each other better.\"<ref name=\"Blabbermouth\">{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/theory-of-a-deadman-to-release-say-nothing-album-in-january-history-of-violence-video-available/|title=Theory of a Deadman to Release 'Say Nothing' Album in January; \"History of Violence\" Video Available|date=September 25, 2019|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe album adds elements of [[brass instruments]], [[Gospel music|gospel choirs]], and [[piano]] to its sound.<ref name=\"Commodore\" /> Connolly commented on the musical composition: \"We're trying to do something we haven't done before on this album and continue to be inspired, and we found that in new instrumentation and different production.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Press Interview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/features/theory-of-a-deadman-history-of-violence-say-nothing-interview/|title=Theory of a Deadman Embrace Newfound Political Identity on 'Say Nothing'|last=Hafke|first=Tim|date=September 25, 2019|website=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> The band found further inspiration after participating in a private tour of [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London, specifically referencing [[The Beatles]]' album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', which contained tracks recorded there in 1967.<ref name=\"Alternative Press Interview\" />\n\n''Say Nothing'''s lead single, \"[[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\", talks about [[Domestic violence|domestic abuse]], and was released concurrently with its music video on September 25, 2019. In an interview with ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'', Connolly stated, \"I think with the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo movement]], there's been a lot of empowerment of women, which has been fantastic. We wanted to have a video that not only reflected the lyrics of the track but also left the viewer feeling like there's something they can do if they've been affected by something like this. That's a big issue\u2014a lot of women don't come forward. I think it's important for people to feel like there's other people out there that can help.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Press Interview\" />\n\n\"Strangers\" is a song that examines the polarizing effect of politics on society and how political and social events created a new generation of activists;<ref name=\"Artist Waves\" /> Connolly stressed his beliefs in not making the politically-charged song seem biased.<ref name=\"Substream Interview\" /> The record's title track\u2014\"Say Nothing\"\u2014vocalizes the lack of communication seen in relationships, which is one issue that Connolly admits led to his divorce from ex-wife Christine.<ref name=\"Billboard Say Nothing\" />\n\nExploring the topic of depression and anxiety, \"World Keeps Spinning\", Connolly's goal with this song's lyrics was to reflect on his personal experiences of depression, and to provide consolation to those experiencing despair.<ref name=\"Substream Interview\" /><ref name=\"American Songwriter\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/theory-of-a-deadman-world-keeps-spinning-behind-the-song/|title=Theory Shares Their Experience with Mental Illness in \"World Keeps Spinning\"|last=Bennett|first=Macie|date=January 31, 2020|website=[[American Songwriter]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> He found the writing process more complicated when touching on sensitive and personal subjects.<ref name=\"American Songwriter\" />\n\n==Recording==\nProduction took place at Kensaltown Recording Studios, an establishment owned and run by the producer of ''Say Nothing'', [[Martin Terefe]]. The band recorded the 10 tracks for the record from April to May 2019 in London, spending six weeks in an [[Airbnb]].<ref name=\"Recording Record Seven\" /><ref name=\"Commodore\" /> Additional recording was completed by Connolly at The Panic Room in [[Burbank, California]] and by [[Nikolaj Torp Larsen]] at Eastcote Studio 4 in London.<ref name=\"Say Nothing Liner\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Say Nothing|others=[[Theory of a Deadman]]|year=2020|type=Liner notes|publisher=[[604 Records]], [[Roadrunner Records]], [[Atlantic Records]]|id=016861739423}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and singles==\nIn an effort to promote the album, three songs were released to the public before the official release of ''Say Nothing''\u2014\"History of Violence\" on September 25, 2020, \"Strangers\" on November 8, and the title track on December 13.<ref name=\"Parade\">{{cite web|url=https://parade.com/948753/laurawhitmore/theorys-strangers-boldly-rocks-a-stark-anthem-on-the-state-of-humanity/|title=Theory's \"Strangers\" Boldly Rocks a Stark Anthem on the State of Humanity|last=Whitmore|first=Laura B.|date=November 8, 2019|website=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> \"World Keeps Spinning\" was released on January 31, 2020, in concurrence with the album; the music video premiered on the band's official [[YouTube]] channel.<ref name=\"American Songwriter\" /> Pre-orders for ''Say Nothing'' were made available on September 25, with \"History of Violence\" included as an [[Music download|instant grat download]]; \"Strangers\" was also included starting on November 8.<ref name=\"Parade\" /><ref name=\"Say Nothing Announced\">{{cite tweet|user=TheoryMusic|number=1176874721499144192|date=September 25, 2019|title=We are excited to reveal that our new album, Say Nothing, releases 1.31.20! Pre-order/pre-save: https://theory.lnk.to/hov  Our new single \"History of Violence\" is out now. The official video premieres at 12PM EST today on @YouTube. We\u2019ll be live chatting: https://youtu.be/hgHwXM7GYuk|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe band headlined a Canadian tour, beginning on January 31, 2020, to coincide with the release of the album.<ref name=\"Blabbermouth\" /> An American tour with [[10 Years (band)|10 Years]] was to officially commence on April 9; with respects to the suspensions of large-scale gatherings due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus global pandemic]], the tour was postponed to an unannounced date.<ref name=\"Spring Tour\">{{cite tweet|user=TheoryMusic|number=1240343424957583366|date=March 18, 2020|title=TOUR UPDATE: Due to the ongoing COVID-19 outbreak & ban on public gatherings, we have decided to postpone our upcoming Spring headline tour (4/09 - 5/16) to a later date. To be clear, we are not cancelling, just moving dates to an undisclosed time \u2014 all tickets will be honored.|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The group is scheduled to tour in the United States with [[Breaking Benjamin]], [[Bush (British band)|Bush]], [[Saint Asonia]], and Canadian musician Cory Marks, beginning on July 15 in Bristow, VA, and culminating on September 8 in Mountain View, CA.<ref name=\"Summer Tour\">{{cite tweet|user=TheoryMusic|number=1236039933321764866|date=March 6, 2020|title=Tickets are on sale now! We can\u2019t wait to hit the road this summer with our boys from Breaking Benjamin and Bush.|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 54/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/say-nothing/theory-of-a-deadman|title=Say Nothing by Theory of a Deadman|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/say-nothing-mw0003322158|title=Say Nothing \u2013 Theory of a Deadman|last=Monger|first=James Christopher|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n|rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"American Songwriter Review\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/rock-veterans-theory-changes-with-the-times-on-say-nothing/hal-horowitz/|title=Rock Veterans Theory Changes with the Times on 'Say Nothing'|last=Horowitz|first=Hal|date=January 29, 2020|website=[[American Songwriter]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Magazine]]''\n|rev3Score = Positive<ref name=\"Metacritic\" />\n|rev4 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n|rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Kerrang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-theory-say-nothing/|title=Album Review: Theory \u2013 Say Nothing|last=Slessor|first=Dan|website=[[Kerrang!]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe album received mostly mixed reviews according to four critics on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"Metacritic\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Say Nothing'' track listing\n| total_length  = 35:01\n| title1        = Black Hole in Your Heart\n| writer1       = Tyler Connolly, Dave Brenner, Dean Back, Joey Dandeneau, Christine Connolly\n| length1       = 3:34\n| title2        = [[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\n| writer2       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length2       = 3:55\n| title3        = Affluenza\n| writer3       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length3       = 3:37\n| title4        = Say Nothing\n| writer4       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length4       = 3:36\n| title5        = Strangers\n| writer5       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length5       = 3:26\n| title6        = Ted Bundy\n| writer6       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau\n| length6       = 3:32\n| title7        = World Keeps Spinning\n| writer7       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau\n| length7       = 3:35\n| title8        = Quicksand\n| writer8       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length8       = 3:01\n| title9        = White Boy\n| writer9       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau\n| length9       = 4:11\n| title10       = It's All Good\n| writer10      = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau\n| length10      = 2:34\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Say Nothing'' and [[AllMusic]].<ref name=\"Say Nothing Liner\" /><ref name=\"All Music Say Nothing Credits\">{{cite web|title=Say Nothing \u2013 Theory of a Deadman \u2013 Credits|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/say-nothing-mw0003322158/credits|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n{{col-float}}\n'''Theory of a Deadman'''\n* Tyler Connolly \u2013 vocals, guitar, piano\n* Dave Brenner \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n* Dean Back \u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], backing vocals\n* Joey Dandeneau \u2013 drums, backing vocals\n{{col-float-break}}\n'''\"Black Hole in Your Heart\", \"Quicksand\", and \"Say Nothing\"'''\n* David Davidson \u2013 violin, strings arrangement\n* David Angell \u2013 violin\n* Monisa Angell \u2013 viola\n* Carole Rabinowitz \u2013 cello\n{{col-float-end}}\n{{col-float}}\n'''Production'''\n* [[Neal Avron]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing|mixing]]\n* Tyler Connolly \u2013 [[Audio engineering|engineering]], [[Record producer|producing]], [[Programming (music)|programming]]\n* Clem Cherry \u2013 engineering, programming\n* Dyre Gormsen \u2013 engineering\n* [[Ted Jensen]] \u2013 [[mastering engineer]]ing\n* Jorge Arango Kure \u2013 engineering\n* Taylor Pollert \u2013 engineering (strings)\n* [[Glen Scott]] \u2013 programming\n* Scott Skrzynski \u2013 mixing\n* Martin Terefe \u2013 producing\n* [[Nikolaj Torp Larsen]] \u2013 engineering\n* [[Oskar Winberg]] \u2013 engineering, programming\n{{col-float-break}}\n'''\"Ted Bundy\"'''\n* David Davidson \u2013 violin, strings arrangement\n* Oskar Winberg \u2013 horns arrangement, strings arrangement\n* Sven Lindvall \u2013 horns arrangement, tuba\n* David Angell \u2013 violin\n* Monisa Angell \u2013 viola\n* Carole Rabinowitz \u2013 cello\n* Leif Lindvall \u2013 trumpet\n{{col-float-end}}\n'''Locations'''\n* Recorded at Kensaltown Recording Studios ([[London]]), The Panic Room ([[Burbank, California]]), and Eastcote Studio 4 (London)\n* Mixed at The Casita ([[Hollywood|Hollywood, California]])\n* Mastered at [[Ted Jensen#Studio|Sterling Sound]] ([[Nashville, Tennessee]])\n* Strings recorded at The Library (Nashville, Tennessee)\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Sales chart performance for ''Say Nothing''\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[ARIA Digital Album Chart|Australian Digital Albums]] ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.aria.com.au/pdfs/1FAF5F78CAC02455E60C0DB8970BCE15B325448ADF880DA5DF9FD10A8B3FF9B8/ARIA%20Digital%20Albums%20Chart.pdf?seq=30|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Digital Albums|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=February 10, 2020|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 35\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|51|artist=Theory of a Deadman|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|116|M|url=https://twitter.com/billboardcharts/status/1226909337056088065|title=Debuts on this week's #Billboard200 (2/2)|work=Billboard on Twitter|artist=Theory of a Deadman|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardAlternative|5|artist=Theory of a Deadman|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRock|14|artist=Theory of a Deadman|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 200|''Rolling Stone'' Top 200]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/albums/2020-02-06/|title=Top 200 Albums|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n| 127\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of 2020 albums]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Theory of a Deadman}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Theory of a Deadman albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Martin Terefe]]\n[[Category:604 Records albums]]\n[[Category:Roadrunner Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->\n| name       = Say Nothing\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Theory of a Deadman]]\n| cover      = TOAD_Say_Nothing_album_cover.jpg\n| alt        = An image of palm trees seen on a blue background as if being seen as a reflection on a body of water. The entire image is surrounded by a thick black border. The word \"Theory\" is seen in the middle while the phrase \"Say Nothing\" is displayed in the bottom right corner.\n| border     = yes\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|01|31|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = April\u2013May 2019<ref name=\"Recording Record Seven\">Recording dates for ''Say Nothing'':\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BvIQv4AHoMD/|title=Record 7 is upon us!! We start recording in april in jolly ole England with #martinterefe so stay tuned!! #theory #record7|date=March 17, 2019|publisher=[[Instagram]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/ByIG9JZFMgi/|title=@theory_dean slappin da bass. Today is officially our last day here before we fly home and get ready for summer touring!! #theory7 #london|date=May 31, 2019|publisher=Instagram|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n| studio     = Kensaltown, The Panic Room, Eastcote Studio 4\n| genre      =\n| length     = 35:01\n| label      =\n* [[604 Records|604]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n* [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n| producer   = [[Martin Terefe]]\n| prev_title = [[Wake Up Call (Theory of a Deadman album)|Wake Up Call]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Say Nothing\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\n | single1date = September 25, 2019\n | single2     = World Keeps Spinning\n | single2date = January 24, 2020\n }}\n}}\n\n'''''Say Nothing''''' is the seventh studio album by Canadian rock band [[Theory of a Deadman]], released on January 31, 2020, through [[604 Records]] in Canada and [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] and [[Roadrunner Records]] in the United States. The record contains lyrics about such issues as domestic violence and racism. The band opted to continue their collaboration with Swedish music producer [[Martin Terefe]]\u2014who worked with them on their previous album ''[[Wake Up Call (Theory of a Deadman album)|Wake Up Call]]''\u2014returning to [[London]] in April 2019. Their prior album marked the group's departure from their usual hard rock sound to a more pop- and pop rock-infused style and was met with mixed reviews from critics.\n\n==Background and development==\n[[Theory of a Deadman]]'s sound had been firmly rooted in the [[Alternative rock|alternative]] and [[hard rock]] genres since the band signed a record deal with [[Chad Kroeger]]'s [[604 Records]] in 2001. Lead singer Tyler Connolly stated that after the release of their fourth studio album, ''[[The Truth Is... (Theory of a Deadman album)|The Truth Is...]]'', in 2011, the band was receiving pressure from their record label to create an album that was \"more poppy\". He believed the label was \"getting tired of [their] fun rock stuff\" and \"wanted to hear something different\". The band responded to this pressure with the release of their fifth studio album, ''[[Savages (Theory of a Deadman album)|Savages]]'', in 2014, which Connolly described as the \"opposite\" of their record label's wishes.<ref name=\"NRR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalrockreview.com/interviews/tyler-connolly-of-theory-of-a-deadman|title=Tyler Connolly of Theory of a Deadman|last=Kennedy|first=Adam|date=March 6, 2016|publisher=[[National Rock Review]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170914033121/http://www.nationalrockreview.com/interviews/tyler-connolly-of-theory-of-a-deadman|archive-date=September 14, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Los Angeles-based music producer [[Howard Benson]] worked with the band on ''Savages'' as well as three of their previous albums,<ref name=\"SurreyNow-Leader\">{{cite web|url=https://www.surreynowleader.com/entertainment/rx-medicate-the-biggest-song-of-theory-of-a-deadmans-16-year-career-north-delta-bassist-raves/|title='Rx (Medicate)' the Biggest Song of Theory of a Deadman's 16-year Career, North Delta Bassist Raves|last=Zillich|first=Tom|website=[[The Now (newspaper)|Surrey Now-Leader]]|date=December 15, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518173856/https://www.surreynowleader.com/entertainment/rx-medicate-the-biggest-song-of-theory-of-a-deadmans-16-year-career-north-delta-bassist-raves/|archive-date=May 18, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but the group felt they wanted something different for their future records. Connolly stated that their [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]] team mentioned Swedish music producer, [[Martin Terefe]], who was known for working with pop rock music artists such as [[Jason Mraz]], [[James Blunt]], and [[Train (band)|Train]], and was interested in collaborating with the group. Theory of a Deadman spent seven weeks in London in 2016, recording at Terefe's Kensaltown Studios.<ref name=\"SurreyNow-Leader\" /><ref name=\"Two Doods Reviews 1\">{{cite AV media|title=10 Questions with Tyler Connolly from Theory of a Deadman|url=https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|time=2:14|publisher=Two Doods Reviews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611080003/https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe band's sixth studio album ''[[Wake Up Call (Theory of a Deadman album)|Wake Up Call]]'', released in October 2017, has been described by critics as a departure from Theory of a Deadman's usual hard rock foundation, moving into [[Pop music|pop]] and [[pop rock]] territory.<ref name=\"Alternative Addiction\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/Review/1661|title=Album Review of Wake Up Call by Theory of a Deadman|website=[[Alternative Addiction]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308100837/http://www.alternativeaddiction.com/Review/1661|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Spokesman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/nov/09/theory-of-a-deadman-trade-hard-rock-for-pop-rock-o/#/0|title=Theory of a Deadman Trade Hard Rock for Pop-rock on 'Wake Up Call'|last=Podplesky|first=Azaria|website=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|date=November 9, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231211932/http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/nov/09/theory-of-a-deadman-trade-hard-rock-for-pop-rock-o/#/0|archive-date=December 31, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The band credited this shift to Connolly, the group's primary songwriter, acquiring and learning how to play the [[piano]] prior to the album's recording. Connolly expressed feeling creatively exhausted, stating, \"For some reason, [on] this album, I felt tapped on the guitar side. I felt like every riff was written.\"<ref name=\"Two Doods Reviews 2\">{{cite AV media|title=10 Questions with Tyler Connolly from Theory of a Deadman|url=https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|time=1:45|publisher=Two Doods Reviews|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611080003/https://twodoodsreviews.com/2017/12/10/10-questions-with-tyler-connolly-from-theory-of-a-deadman/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bassist Dean Back agreed, saying, \"During the writing process, Tyler\u2019s go-to was to always pick up a guitar and write with that. He pushed himself through and instead of writing with the guitar he used a piano he has in his house. ... I think writing on the piano opened up another creative realm in him.\"<ref name=\"AXS1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-theory-of-a-deadman-s-dean-back-on-their-new-sound-for-wake--124476|title=Interview: Theory of a Deadman\u2019s Dean Back on Their New Sound for 'Wake Up Call'|last=Allegrezza|first=Kim|publisher=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|date=October 22, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141119/https://www.axs.com/interview-theory-of-a-deadman-s-dean-back-on-their-new-sound-for-wake--124476|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The album was met with mixed reviews from critics with some praising the lyrical maturity that was lacking in previous albums, and others criticizing it for the sudden change in genre.<ref name=\"Wake Up Call Review 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/wake-up-call-mw0003090487|title=Wake Up Call \u2013 Theory of a Deadman|last=Monter|first=James Christopher|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613020229/https://www.allmusic.com/album/wake-up-call-mw0003090487|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Wake Up Call Review 2\">\n{{cite web|url=http://www.uberrock.co.uk/cd-reviews/31-november-cd/19761-theory-of-a-deadman-wake-up-call-roadrunner-records604-records.html|title=Theory of a Deadman \u2013 'Wake Up Call'|last=D|first=Jonni|work=\u00dcber Rock|date=November 13, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180116140441/http://www.uberrock.co.uk/cd-reviews/31-november-cd/19761-theory-of-a-deadman-wake-up-call-roadrunner-records604-records.html|archive-date=January 16, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}\n</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n''Say Nothing'' has been described by the band as a \"continuation of the last record\",<ref name=\"Substream Interview\">{{cite web|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2020/01/interview-theory-connolly-world-spinning/|title=Exclusive: Theory Drop Video for \"World Keeps Spinning\" + Interview w/ Tyler Connolly|last=White|first=Logan|date=January 31, 2020|website=[[Substream Magazine]]|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and Connolly acknowledged a sense of anxiety while recording the album due to the pressure created by the success of ''Wake Up Call'''s [[lead single]], \"[[Rx (Medicate)]]\" (a song that addresses [[Substance abuse|prescription drug abuse]]).<ref name=\"Billboard Say Nothing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8546128/theory-of-a-deadman-say-nothing|title=Theory of a Deadman's 'Say Nothing': Premiere|last=Graff|first=Gary|authorlink=Gary Graff|date=December 13, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Although Theory of a Deadman have avoided having their lyrics surround social and political issues, the positive feedback they received for \"Rx (Medicate)\" influenced their decision to speak about important topics related to [[domestic violence]], [[racism]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and [[anxiety]], and politics.<ref name=\"Artist Waves\">{{cite web|url=https://artistwaves.com/speaking-up-with-say-nothing-by-tyler-connolly-theory-of-a-deadman/|title=Speaking Up with \"Say Nothing\" by: Tyler Connolly / Theory of a Deadman|last=Connolly|first=Tyler|date=November 5, 2019|publisher=Artist Waves|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Connolly said, \"This album allowed me to say all of the things that were on my mind earlier, but I was too afraid to say. Our previous material was pretty much all relationship-driven. Everything was about me being unhappy. This one was about what's going on in the world, the state of American politics, and everything else. It was a completely different way of writing for us.\"<ref name=\"Commodore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.commodoreballroom.com/view-all/2020/1/31/theory|title=Say Nothing World Tour 2020|publisher=[[Commodore Ballroom]]|accessdate=September 26, 2019}}</ref> Guitarist Dave Brenner added, \"I look at the record as a microcosm of our current era. It's a reminder to look inward at what's happening and what we're becoming. ... Maybe we can give the world a little solace and encourage everyone to treat each other better.\"<ref name=\"Blabbermouth\">{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/theory-of-a-deadman-to-release-say-nothing-album-in-january-history-of-violence-video-available/|title=Theory of a Deadman to Release 'Say Nothing' Album in January; \"History of Violence\" Video Available|date=September 25, 2019|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe album adds elements of [[brass instruments]], [[Gospel music|gospel choirs]], and [[piano]] to its sound.<ref name=\"Commodore\" /> Connolly commented on the musical composition: \"We're trying to do something we haven't done before on this album and continue to be inspired, and we found that in new instrumentation and different production.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Press Interview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/features/theory-of-a-deadman-history-of-violence-say-nothing-interview/|title=Theory of a Deadman Embrace Newfound Political Identity on 'Say Nothing'|last=Hafke|first=Tim|date=September 25, 2019|website=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> The band found further inspiration after participating in a private tour of [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London, specifically referencing [[The Beatles]]' album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'', which contained tracks recorded there in 1967.<ref name=\"Alternative Press Interview\" />\n\n''Say Nothing'''s lead single, \"[[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\", talks about [[Domestic violence|domestic abuse]], and was released concurrently with its music video on September 25, 2019. In an interview with ''[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]]'', Connolly stated, \"I think with the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo movement]], there's been a lot of empowerment of women, which has been fantastic. We wanted to have a video that not only reflected the lyrics of the track but also left the viewer feeling like there's something they can do if they've been affected by something like this. That's a big issue\u2014a lot of women don't come forward. I think it's important for people to feel like there's other people out there that can help.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Press Interview\" />\n\n\"Strangers\" is a song that examines the polarizing effect of politics on society and how political and social events created a new generation of activists;<ref name=\"Artist Waves\" /> Connolly stressed his beliefs in not making the politically-charged song seem biased.<ref name=\"Substream Interview\" /> The record's title track\u2014\"Say Nothing\"\u2014vocalizes the lack of communication seen in relationships, which is one issue that Connolly admits led to his divorce from ex-wife Christine.<ref name=\"Billboard Say Nothing\" />\n\nExploring the topic of depression and anxiety, \"World Keeps Spinning\", Connolly's goal with this song's lyrics was to reflect on his personal experiences of depression, and to provide consolation to those experiencing despair.<ref name=\"Substream Interview\" /><ref name=\"American Songwriter\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/theory-of-a-deadman-world-keeps-spinning-behind-the-song/|title=Theory Shares Their Experience with Mental Illness in \"World Keeps Spinning\"|last=Bennett|first=Macie|date=January 31, 2020|website=[[American Songwriter]]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> He found the writing process more complicated when touching on sensitive and personal subjects.<ref name=\"American Songwriter\" />\n\n==Recording==\nProduction took place at Kensaltown Recording Studios, an establishment owned and run by the producer of ''Say Nothing'', [[Martin Terefe]]. The band recorded the 10 tracks for the record from April to May 2019 in London, spending six weeks in an [[Airbnb]].<ref name=\"Recording Record Seven\" /><ref name=\"Commodore\" /> Additional recording was completed by Connolly at The Panic Room in [[Burbank, California]] and by [[Nikolaj Torp Larsen]] at Eastcote Studio 4 in London.<ref name=\"Say Nothing Liner\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Say Nothing|others=[[Theory of a Deadman]]|year=2020|type=Liner notes|publisher=[[604 Records]], [[Roadrunner Records]], [[Atlantic Records]]|id=016861739423}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and singles==\nIn an effort to promote the album, three songs were released to the public before the official release of ''Say Nothing''\u2014\"History of Violence\" on September 25, 2020, \"Strangers\" on November 8, and the title track on December 13.<ref name=\"Parade\">{{cite web|url=https://parade.com/948753/laurawhitmore/theorys-strangers-boldly-rocks-a-stark-anthem-on-the-state-of-humanity/|title=Theory's \"Strangers\" Boldly Rocks a Stark Anthem on the State of Humanity|last=Whitmore|first=Laura B.|date=November 8, 2019|website=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> \"World Keeps Spinning\" was released on January 31, 2020, in concurrence with the album; the music video premiered on the band's official [[YouTube]] channel.<ref name=\"American Songwriter\" /> Pre-orders for ''Say Nothing'' were made available on September 25, with \"History of Violence\" included as an [[Music download|instant grat download]]; \"Strangers\" was also included starting on November 8.<ref name=\"Parade\" /><ref name=\"Say Nothing Announced\">{{cite tweet|user=TheoryMusic|number=1176874721499144192|date=September 25, 2019|title=We are excited to reveal that our new album, Say Nothing, releases 1.31.20! Pre-order/pre-save: https://theory.lnk.to/hov  Our new single \"History of Violence\" is out now. The official video premieres at 12PM EST today on @YouTube. We\u2019ll be live chatting: https://youtu.be/hgHwXM7GYuk|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe band headlined a Canadian tour, beginning on January 31, 2020, to coincide with the release of the album.<ref name=\"Blabbermouth\" /> An American tour with [[10 Years (band)|10 Years]] was to officially commence on April 9; with respects to the suspensions of large-scale gatherings due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus global pandemic]], the tour was postponed to an unannounced date.<ref name=\"Spring Tour\">{{cite tweet|user=TheoryMusic|number=1240343424957583366|date=March 18, 2020|title=TOUR UPDATE: Due to the ongoing COVID-19 outbreak & ban on public gatherings, we have decided to postpone our upcoming Spring headline tour (4/09 - 5/16) to a later date. To be clear, we are not cancelling, just moving dates to an undisclosed time \u2014 all tickets will be honored.|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The group is scheduled to tour in the United States with [[Breaking Benjamin]], [[Bush (British band)|Bush]], [[Saint Asonia]], and Canadian musician Cory Marks, beginning on July 15 in Bristow, VA, and culminating on September 8 in Mountain View, CA.<ref name=\"Summer Tour\">{{cite tweet|user=TheoryMusic|number=1236039933321764866|date=March 6, 2020|title=Tickets are on sale now! We can\u2019t wait to hit the road this summer with our boys from Breaking Benjamin and Bush.|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n{{Album ratings\n|MC = 54/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/say-nothing/theory-of-a-deadman|title=Say Nothing by Theory of a Deadman|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/say-nothing-mw0003322158|title=Say Nothing \u2013 Theory of a Deadman|last=Monger|first=James Christopher|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[American Songwriter]]''\n|rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"American Songwriter Review\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/rock-veterans-theory-changes-with-the-times-on-say-nothing/hal-horowitz/|title=Rock Veterans Theory Changes with the Times on 'Say Nothing'|last=Horowitz|first=Hal|date=January 29, 2020|website=[[American Songwriter]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Magazine]]''\n|rev3Score = Positive<ref name=\"Metacritic\" />\n|rev4 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n|rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"Kerrang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-theory-say-nothing/|title=Album Review: Theory \u2013 Say Nothing|last=Slessor|first=Dan|website=[[Kerrang!]]|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe album received mostly mixed reviews according to four critics on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"Metacritic\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| total_length  = 35:01\n| title1        = Black Hole in Your Heart\n| writer1       = Tyler Connolly, Dave Brenner, Dean Back, Joey Dandeneau, Christine Connolly\n| length1       = 3:34\n| title2        = [[History of Violence (song)|History of Violence]]\n| writer2       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length2       = 3:55\n| title3        = Affluenza\n| writer3       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length3       = 3:37\n| title4        = Say Nothing\n| writer4       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length4       = 3:36\n| title5        = Strangers\n| writer5       = T. Connolly, Brenner, Back, Dandeneau, C. Connolly\n| length5       =