{"title_page": "Rapha\u00ebl Wicky", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Raphael Wicky\n| image = Rapha\u00ebl Wicky 2017.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Wicky coaching Basel in 2017\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Leuggern]], Switzerland\n| height = 1.78m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]] (head coach)\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1984\u20131990\n| youthclubs1 = Steg\n| youthyears2 = 1990\u20131993\n| youthclubs2 = [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20131997\n| clubs1 = [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n| caps1 = 130\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 1997\u20132000\n| clubs2 = [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]\n| caps2 = 92\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2001\n| clubs3 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps3 = 11\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2001\u20132007\n| clubs4 = [[Hamburger SV]]\n| caps4 = 126\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2007\n| clubs5 = [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2008\n| clubs6 = [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]]\n| caps6 = 5\n| goals6 = 0\n| totalcaps = 369\n| totalgoals = 8\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 75\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2009\u20132010\n| managerclubs1 = [[FC Thun]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2010\u20132013\n| managerclubs2 = [[Servette FC|Servette]] (youth)\n| manageryears3 = 2013\u20132016\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Basel]] (U-18)\n| manageryears4 = 2016\u20132017\n| managerclubs4 = [[FC Basel]] (U-21)\n| manageryears5 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs5 = [[FC Basel]]\n| medaltemplates = \n| managerclubs6 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U17]]\n| manageryears6 = 2019\n| managerclubs7 = [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]]\n| manageryears7 = 2019\u2013\n\n}}\n'''Raphael Wicky''' (born 26 April 1977) is a Swiss [[Association football|football]] coach and a former player who is the head coach of [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]] of [[Major League Soccer]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chicagofirefc.com/post/2019/12/27/chicago-fire-fc-names-raphael-wicky-head-coach |title=Chicago Fire FC Names Raphael Wicky Head Coach &#124; Chicago Fire FC|date=27 December 2019}}</ref> He was a [[Midfielder#Defensive|defensive midfielder]] who could also play in [[Defender (association football)|defence]] and was known for his combative style.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/switzerland/players_to_watch/3674669.stm |title=Raphael Wicky |publisher=BBC |access-date=21 March 2012|date=25 May 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Leuggern]] in the canton of [[Aargau]], Wicky started his career with [[FC Sion]], and went on to represent [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. On 25 January 2001, he joined [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], then in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wicky llega a Madrid confiado en subir al Atl\u00e9tico a Primera|trans-title=Wicky arrives at Madrid trusting Atl\u00e9tico to rise to ''Primera''|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/abci-wicky-llega-madrid-confiado-subir-atletico-primera-200101250300-7590_noticia.html?ref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=ABC |date=25 January 2001 |language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\nAfter only 11 games in Spain, he returned to the [[Bundesliga]] on 6 December 2001, signing for [[Hamburger SV]] until the end of the season with the option to extend until June 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=El atl\u00e9tico Wicky ficha por el Hamburgo hasta final de temporada |trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico's Wicky signs for Hamburg until the end of the season|url=https://as.com/futbol/2001/12/06/mas_futbol/1007593239_850215.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=6 December 2001 |language=Spanish}}</ref> He returned to Sion on a three-year contract on 23 August 2007, after losing first-choice status with Hamburg under manager [[Huub Stevens]] following a period of injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wicky signs on at Sion |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/01c4-0e6e6bed8af7-c9b5eec77929-1000--wicky-signs-on-at-sion/?referrer=%2Fuefaeuropaleague%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D574372 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=23 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nWicky signed on a free transfer with [[Los Angeles]]-based [[Major League Soccer]] side [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]] in February 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/team_news.jsp?ymd=20080204&content_id=137643&vkey=pr_cdc&fext=.jsp&team=t120 |title=Chivas signs Wicky |publisher=mlsnet.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221173357/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/team_news.jsp?ymd=20080204&content_id=137643&vkey=pr_cdc&fext=.jsp&team=t120 |archive-date=21 February 2009 }}</ref> Wicky made his debut as a substitute in Chivas' season opener against [[FC Dallas]] on 30 March. His season was cut short due to ankle injury, making just five appearances in his first MLS season. He underwent surgery to repair the injury in July 2008 and was placed on the team's season-ending injury list on 15 September.\n\nOn 26 January 2009, Chivas USA announced that they had re-signed Wicky to a one-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/01/chivas-usa-announced-on-monday-that.html |title=Wicky Re-Signs With Chivas For '09 |date=26 January 2009 |publisher=MLS Daily |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201072750/http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/01/chivas-usa-announced-on-monday-that.html |archive-date=1 February 2009 |access-date=26 January 2009}}</ref> Five weeks later, on 3 March, he announced his retirement from professional football, citing \"personal reasons.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/03/chivas-usas-wicky-announces-retirement.html |title=Chivas USA's Wicky Announces Retirement |date=2 March 2009 |publisher=MLS Daily |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307124839/http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/03/chivas-usas-wicky-announces-retirement.html |archive-date=7 March 2009 |access-date=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nInternationally, Wicky was part of the [[Switzerland national football team|Swiss national teams]] at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]] and [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keller |first1=Marco |title=La Suisse fait monter la pression|trans-title=Switzerland turn up the pressure |url=https://fr.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/news/0254-0d7b5f8c97f1-f701d5ba7d63-1000--la-suisse-fait-monter-la-pression/ |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=11 June 2004 |language=French}}</ref> as well as at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]].\n\nIn 75 appearances, he scored one goal, to open a 3\u20131 win away to the Faroe Islands in qualification for the last of those tournaments on 4 June 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2006 qualifying review |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4606337.stm |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 June 2005}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Switzerland's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/6425/Raphael_Wicky.html |title=Wicky, Rapha\u00ebl |publisher=National Football Teams |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 4 June 2005 || [[Svangaskar\u00f0]], [[Toftir]], [[Faroe Islands]] || {{fb|FRO}} || align=center | 1\u20130 || align=center | 3\u20131 || [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 4|2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Managerial career==\nUpon retiring, Wicky coached the youth teams of [[FC Thun]] in 2009<ref>[http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/Ratschlaege-eines-Auszubildenden/story/30272796 Ratschl\u00e4ge eines Auszubildenden]\u201a bernerzeitung.ch, 20 November 2009</ref> and a year later [[Servette FC|Servette]].<ref>[https://www.blick.ch/sport/fussball/nach-seinem-ruecktritt-wird-der-ex-nati-spieler-trainer-wicky-uebernimmt-servettes-nachwuchs-id55516.html Wicky \u00fcbernimmt Servettes Nachwuchs]\u201a blick.ch, 31 July 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he moved into the youth ranks of [[FC Basel]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/season=2017/clubs/club=2605548/squad/index.html |title=UEFA Youth League FC Basel 2016-17 squad |date=13 September 2016 |publisher=[[UEFA]]}}</ref> He became first-team manager on 21 April 2017, replacing [[Urs Fischer]] after a boardroom change.<ref>[https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2017/04/21/Raphael-Wicky-ist-ab-Sommer-2017-der-neue-Cheftrai RAPHAEL WICKY IST AB SOMMER 2017 DER NEUE TRAINER DES FCB]\u201a fcb.ch, 21 April 2017</ref> Days later, the team wrapped up an eighth consecutive league title,<ref>{{cite news |title=Le FC B\u00e2le est (encore) champion de Suisse|trans-title=FC Basel is (still) champion of Switzerland |url=https://www.letemps.ch/sport/fc-bale-champion-suisse |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Le Temps |date=29 April 2017 |language=French}}</ref> and on 25 May won the [[Swiss Cup]] with a 3\u20130 victory over [[FC Sion]] at the [[Stade de Gen\u00e8ve]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coupe de Suisse: B\u00e2le met un terme \u00e0 la l\u00e9gende de Sion en finale|trans-title=Swiss Cup: Basel put an end to Sion's fairytale in the final |url=https://www.rts.ch/sport/football/suisse/coupe-de-suisse/8650315-coupe-de-suisse-bale-met-un-terme-a-la-legende-de-sion-en-finale.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=RTS |date=25 May 2017 |language=French}}</ref> On 26 July 2018, having finishing as runner-up in both competitions and started the new season poorly, he was sacked.<ref>{{cite news |title=Football: Wicky mis \u00e0 la porte par le FC B\u00e2le!|trans-title=Football: Wicky shown the door by FC Basel! |url=https://www.lematin.ch/sports/football/wicky-mis-porte-fc-ble/story/31262921 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Le Matin |date=26 July 2018 |language=French}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2019, Wicky was named the head coach of the United States Under-17 Men's National Team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2019/03/raphael-wicky-named-head-coach-of-us-under17-mens-national-team |title=Raphael Wicky Named Head Coach of U.S. Under-17 Men's National Team |website=ussoccer.com}}</ref> On 27 December 2019, he was named the head coach of [[Major League Soccer]] side [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title=\nRapha\u00ebl Wicky career sheet|url=https://www.footballdatabase.eu/en/player/details/2897-raphael-wicky |work=footballdatabase |publisher=footballdatabase |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\t\t\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Team\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Nat\n! rowspan=\"2\" |From\n! rowspan=\"2\"|To\n! colspan=\"8\" |Record\t\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\t\t\t\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Basel]]\n|{{Flagicon|Switzerland}}\n|align=left|3 June 2017\n|align=left|26 July 2018\n{{WDL|51|29|9|13|for=94|against=54|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Basel: Matches |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/switzerland/fc-basel/2174/|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U17]]\n|{{Flagicon|USA}}\n|align=left|8 March 2019\n|align=left|27 December 2019\n{{WDL|17|9|2|6|for=39|against=27|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=United States U17: Matches |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/united-states/united-states-under-17/5798/|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]]\n|{{Flagicon|USA}}\n|align=left|27 December 2019\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|2|0|1|1|for=2|against=3|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Chicago Fire FC: Matches |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/united-states/chicago-fire/2273/|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|70|38|12|20|for=135|against=84|diff=yes}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Werder Bremen'''\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[1998\u201399 DFB-Pokal|1998\u201399]]; finalist [[1999\u20132000 DFB-Pokal|1999\u20132000]]\n* DFB-Ligapokal finalist: 1999\n* [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]: [[1998 UEFA Intertoto Cup|1998]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.leballonrond.fr/jogo.php?id=4835448 |title=FK Vojvodina 1\u20131 Werder Bremen |publisher=leballonrond.fr |access-date=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Hamburger SV'''\n* [[DFB-Ligapokal]]: 2003\n* [[Bundesliga]] third place: [[2005\u201306 Bundesliga|2005\u201306]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Basel'''\n*[[Swiss Super League]]: [[2016\u201317 Swiss Super League|2016\u201317]]\n*[[Swiss Cup]]: [[2016\u201317 Swiss Cup|2016\u201317]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Fussballdaten|wickyraphael|Rapha\u00ebl Wicky}}\n\n{{Chicago Fire squad}}\n{{Chicago Fire managers}}\n{{Major League Soccer head coaches}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Switzerland squads\n|bg= #d81e05\n|fg= white\n|bordercolor=\n|list1=\n{{Switzerland squad UEFA Euro 1996}}\n{{Switzerland squad UEFA Euro 2004}}\n{{Switzerland squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wicky, Raphael}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss-German people]]\n[[Category:People from Zurzach District]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Swiss footballers]]\n[[Category:Switzerland international footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Sion players]]\n[[Category:SV Werder Bremen players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:Hamburger SV players]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Super League players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2004 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Swiss football managers]]\n[[Category:FC Basel managers]]\n[[Category:Chicago Fire FC coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:Swiss expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer managers in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Raphael Wicky\n| image = Rapha\u00ebl Wicky 2017.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Wicky coaching Basel in 2017\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1977|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Leuggern]], Switzerland\n| height = 1.78m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]] (head coach)\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1984\u20131990\n| youthclubs1 = Steg\n| youthyears2 = 1990\u20131993\n| youthclubs2 = [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20131997\n| clubs1 = [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n| caps1 = 130\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 1997\u20132000\n| clubs2 = [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]\n| caps2 = 92\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2001\n| clubs3 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps3 = 11\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2001\u20132007\n| clubs4 = [[Hamburger SV]]\n| caps4 = 126\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2007\n| clubs5 = [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2008\n| clubs6 = [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]]\n| caps6 = 5\n| goals6 = 0\n| totalcaps = 369\n| totalgoals = 8\n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 75\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2009\u20132010\n| managerclubs1 = [[FC Thun]] (youth)\n| manageryears2 = 2010\u20132013\n| managerclubs2 = [[Servette FC|Servette]] (youth)\n| manageryears3 = 2013\u20132016\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Basel]] (U-18)\n| manageryears4 = 2016\u20132017\n| managerclubs4 = [[FC Basel]] (U-21)\n| manageryears5 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs5 = [[FC Basel]]\n| medaltemplates = \n| managerclubs6 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U17]]\n| manageryears6 = 2019\n| managerclubs7 = [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]]\n| manageryears7 = 2019\u2013\n\n}}\n'''Raphael Wicky''' (born 26 April 1977) is a Swiss [[Association football|football]] coach and a former player who is the head coach of [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]] of [[Major League Soccer]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chicagofirefc.com/post/2019/12/27/chicago-fire-fc-names-raphael-wicky-head-coach |title=Chicago Fire FC Names Raphael Wicky Head Coach &#124; Chicago Fire FC|date=27 December 2019}}</ref> He was a [[Midfielder#Defensive|defensive midfielder]] who could also play in [[Defender (association football)|defence]] and was known for his combative style.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/switzerland/players_to_watch/3674669.stm |title=Raphael Wicky |publisher=BBC |access-date=21 March 2012|date=25 May 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Leuggern]] in the canton of [[Aargau]], Wicky started his career with [[FC Sion]], and went on to represent [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. On 25 January 2001, he joined [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]], then in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wicky llega a Madrid confiado en subir al Atl\u00e9tico a Primera|trans-title=Wicky arrives at Madrid trusting Atl\u00e9tico to rise to ''Primera''|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/abci-wicky-llega-madrid-confiado-subir-atletico-primera-200101250300-7590_noticia.html?ref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=ABC |date=25 January 2001 |language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\nAfter only 11 games in Spain, he returned to the [[Bundesliga]] on 6 December 2001, signing for [[Hamburger SV]] until the end of the season with the option to extend until June 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=El atl\u00e9tico Wicky ficha por el Hamburgo hasta final de temporada |trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico's Wicky signs for Hamburg until the end of the season|url=https://as.com/futbol/2001/12/06/mas_futbol/1007593239_850215.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Diario AS |date=6 December 2001 |language=Spanish}}</ref> He returned to Sion on a three-year contract on 23 August 2007, after losing first-choice status with Hamburg under manager [[Huub Stevens]] following a period of injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wicky signs on at Sion |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/01c4-0e6e6bed8af7-c9b5eec77929-1000--wicky-signs-on-at-sion/?referrer=%2Fuefaeuropaleague%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D574372 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=23 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nWicky signed on a free transfer with [[Los Angeles]]-based [[Major League Soccer]] side [[C.D. Chivas USA|Chivas USA]] in February 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/team_news.jsp?ymd=20080204&content_id=137643&vkey=pr_cdc&fext=.jsp&team=t120 |title=Chivas signs Wicky |publisher=mlsnet.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221173357/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/team_news.jsp?ymd=20080204&content_id=137643&vkey=pr_cdc&fext=.jsp&team=t120 |archive-date=21 February 2009 }}</ref> Wicky made his debut as a substitute in Chivas' season opener against [[FC Dallas]] on 30 March. His season was cut short due to ankle injury, making just five appearances in his first MLS season. He underwent surgery to repair the injury in July 2008 and was placed on the team's season-ending injury list on 15 September.\n\nOn 26 January 2009, Chivas USA announced that they had re-signed Wicky to a one-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/01/chivas-usa-announced-on-monday-that.html |title=Wicky Re-Signs With Chivas For '09 |date=26 January 2009 |publisher=MLS Daily |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201072750/http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/01/chivas-usa-announced-on-monday-that.html |archive-date=1 February 2009 |access-date=26 January 2009}}</ref> Five weeks later, on 3 March, he announced his retirement from professional football, citing \"personal reasons.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/03/chivas-usas-wicky-announces-retirement.html |title=Chivas USA's Wicky Announces Retirement |date=2 March 2009 |publisher=MLS Daily |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307124839/http://www.mls-daily.com/2009/03/chivas-usas-wicky-announces-retirement.html |archive-date=7 March 2009 |access-date=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nInternationally, Wicky was part of the [[Switzerland national football team|Swiss national teams]] at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]] and [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keller |first1=Marco |title=La Suisse fait monter la pression|trans-title=Switzerland turn up the pressure |url=https://fr.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/news/0254-0d7b5f8c97f1-f701d5ba7d63-1000--la-suisse-fait-monter-la-pression/ |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=11 June 2004 |language=French}}</ref> as well as at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]].\n\nIn 75 appearances, he scored one goal, to open a 3\u20131 win away to the Faroe Islands in qualification for the last of those tournaments on 4 June 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2006 qualifying review |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4606337.stm |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 June 2005}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Switzerland's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/6425/Raphael_Wicky.html |title=Wicky, Rapha\u00ebl |publisher=National Football Teams |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! No !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 4 June 2005 || [[Svangaskar\u00f0]], [[Toftir]], [[Faroe Islands]] || {{fb|FRO}} || align=center | '''1'''\u20130 || align=center | 3\u20131 || [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 4|2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|}\n\n==Managerial career==\nUpon retiring, Wicky coached the youth teams of [[FC Thun]] in 2009<ref>[http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/Ratschlaege-eines-Auszubildenden/story/30272796 Ratschl\u00e4ge eines Auszubildenden]\u201a bernerzeitung.ch, 20 November 2009</ref> and a year later [[Servette FC|Servette]].<ref>[https://www.blick.ch/sport/fussball/nach-seinem-ruecktritt-wird-der-ex-nati-spieler-trainer-wicky-uebernimmt-servettes-nachwuchs-id55516.html Wicky \u00fcbernimmt Servettes Nachwuchs]\u201a blick.ch, 31 July 2010</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he moved into the youth ranks of [[FC Basel]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefayouthleague/season=2017/clubs/club=2605548/squad/index.html |title=UEFA Youth League FC Basel 2016-17 squad |date=13 September 2016 |publisher=[[UEFA]]}}</ref> He became first-team manager on 21 April 2017, replacing [[Urs Fischer]] after a boardroom change.<ref>[https://www.fcb.ch/de-CH/News/2017/04/21/Raphael-Wicky-ist-ab-Sommer-2017-der-neue-Cheftrai RAPHAEL WICKY IST AB SOMMER 2017 DER NEUE TRAINER DES FCB]\u201a fcb.ch, 21 April 2017</ref> Days later, the team wrapped up an eighth consecutive league title,<ref>{{cite news |title=Le FC B\u00e2le est (encore) champion de Suisse|trans-title=FC Basel is (still) champion of Switzerland |url=https://www.letemps.ch/sport/fc-bale-champion-suisse |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Le Temps |date=29 April 2017 |language=French}}</ref> and on 25 May won the [[Swiss Cup]] with a 3\u20130 victory over [[FC Sion]] at the [[Stade de Gen\u00e8ve]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coupe de Suisse: B\u00e2le met un terme \u00e0 la l\u00e9gende de Sion en finale|trans-title=Swiss Cup: Basel put an end to Sion's fairytale in the final |url=https://www.rts.ch/sport/football/suisse/coupe-de-suisse/8650315-coupe-de-suisse-bale-met-un-terme-a-la-legende-de-sion-en-finale.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |publisher=RTS |date=25 May 2017 |language=French}}</ref> On 26 July 2018, having finishing as runner-up in both competitions and started the new season poorly, he was sacked.<ref>{{cite news |title=Football: Wicky mis \u00e0 la porte par le FC B\u00e2le!|trans-title=Football: Wicky shown the door by FC Basel! |url=https://www.lematin.ch/sports/football/wicky-mis-porte-fc-ble/story/31262921 |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Le Matin |date=26 July 2018 |language=French}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2019, Wicky was named the head coach of the United States Under-17 Men's National Team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2019/03/raphael-wicky-named-head-coach-of-us-under17-mens-national-team |title=Raphael Wicky Named Head Coach of U.S. Under-17 Men's National Team |website=ussoccer.com}}</ref> On 27 December 2019, he was named the head coach of [[Major League Soccer]] side [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]].<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title=\nRapha\u00ebl Wicky career sheet|url=https://www.footballdatabase.eu/en/player/details/2897-raphael-wicky |work=footballdatabase |publisher=footballdatabase |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"te